DOM: The Document Object Model
What is the DOM?
The DOM is a programming interface for HTML and XML documents. It represents the structure of a webpage as a tree of objects that can be accessed and manipulated with JavaScript.

Key Concepts:
Tree Structure:

Document
└── HTML
    ├── HEAD
    │   ├── TITLE
    │   └── META
    └── BODY
        ├── H1
        ├── P
        └── DIV
            └── BUTTON

Each element, attribute, and text is a node in this tree.

It's NOT the source code:

DOM = Current state of the page after JavaScript modifications

Source HTML = Initial loaded file

Practical Example:
HTML:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
  <h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
  <button>Click me</button>
</body>
</html>

JavaScript DOM Manipulation:

// ACCESS elements
const title = document.getElementById('title');
const button = document.querySelector('button');

// MODIFY content
title.textContent = 'Hello DOM!';
title.style.color = 'blue';

// CREATE new elements
const paragraph = document.createElement('p');
paragraph.textContent = 'I was added dynamically!';
document.body.appendChild(paragraph);

// RESPOND to events
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  title.textContent = 'Clicked!';
});

// REMOVE elements
paragraph.remove();

Common DOM Methods:
Method	Purpose
getElementById()	Get element by ID
querySelector()	Get first matching element
querySelectorAll()	Get all matching elements
createElement()	Create new element
appendChild()	Add element to parent
remove()	Remove element
addEventListener()	Handle events

Why DOM Matters:
Dynamic Updates: Change content without page reload

User Interaction: Respond to clicks, inputs, etc.

Single Page Apps: Create entire applications in one page

API Integration: Display data from servers dynamically

Real-World Analogy:
Think of the DOM as a live blueprint of your house (webpage). JavaScript is the renovation crew that can:

Rearrange furniture (move elements)

Paint walls (change styles)

Add new rooms (create elements)

Remove walls (delete elements)

Pro Tip: Open your browser's Developer Tools (F12) and type document in the console to explore the live DOM of any webpage!

Comprehensive DOM Manipulation Guide
Essential DOM Methods & Properties
1. SELECTION METHODS

// Single element selectors
const el = document.getElementById('myId');
const el = document.querySelector('.myClass'); // CSS selector
const el = document.querySelector('div > p.special');

// Multiple elements
const list = document.getElementsByClassName('item'); // HTMLCollection
const list = document.getElementsByTagName('div'); // HTMLCollection
const list = document.querySelectorAll('.item'); // NodeList (static!)

// Special selectors
const forms = document.forms; // All forms
const images = document.images; // All images
const links = document.links; // All links

2. TRAVERSING THE DOM TREE

const parent = element.parentElement;
const children = element.children; // Element children only
const allChildren = element.childNodes; // Includes text nodes
const firstChild = element.firstElementChild;
const lastChild = element.lastElementChild;
const nextSibling = element.nextElementSibling;
const prevSibling = element.previousElementSibling;

// Closest ancestor matching selector
const closestDiv = element.closest('div.ancestor');

3. CREATING & INSERTING ELEMENTS

// Create element
const newDiv = document.createElement('div');
newDiv.className = 'alert';
newDiv.id = 'alert1';

// Create text node
const text = document.createTextNode('Hello World');

// Append methods
parent.appendChild(newDiv); // End of parent
parent.prepend(newDiv); // Beginning of parent
parent.insertBefore(newDiv, referenceElement); // Before specific child

// Insert adjacent HTML
element.insertAdjacentHTML('beforebegin', '<div>Before</div>');
element.insertAdjacentHTML('afterbegin', '<div>After Start</div>');
element.insertAdjacentHTML('beforeend', '<div>Before End</div>');
element.insertAdjacentHTML('afterend', '<div>After</div>');

// Clone element
const cloned = element.cloneNode(true); // true = deep clone

4. MODIFYING ELEMENTS

// Content manipulation
element.innerHTML = '<strong>Bold</strong> text'; // Parses HTML
element.textContent = 'Plain text only'; // Safer, no HTML parsing
element.innerText = 'Considers styling'; // Aware of CSS

// Attributes
element.setAttribute('data-custom', 'value');
const value = element.getAttribute('data-custom');
element.removeAttribute('data-custom');
element.hasAttribute('data-custom'); // boolean

// Classes
element.classList.add('new-class', 'another-class');
element.classList.remove('old-class');
element.classList.toggle('active'); // Add/remove
element.classList.contains('active'); // boolean
element.className = 'class1 class2'; // Direct string

// Styles
element.style.color = 'red';
element.style.backgroundColor = '#fff';
element.style.cssText = 'color: red; background: blue;'; // Multiple
const computed = getComputedStyle(element); // All computed styles

5. REMOVING ELEMENTS

// Remove element itself
element.remove();

// Remove from parent
parent.removeChild(element);

// Clear all children
while (parent.firstChild) {
    parent.removeChild(parent.firstChild);
}
// OR
parent.innerHTML = '';
